1. The Visual Library (tkinter)
Class: Tk
    Definition: The main engine that creates the basic desktop window for
                the application to live in.

    Usage: Used to open an empty main canvas (window) and, at the end of
            the script, to start a background engine that holds that window continuously
            on the screen so it does not close immediately.

Class: Frame
    Definition: An invisible container or grouping box used to organize
                other items neatly on the screen.

    Usage: Used to keep the layout clean and divide it into logical sections.
           Login boxes are grouped in one invisible frame and form boxes in another frame,
           ensuring everything on the screen does not collapse on top of each other into a messy pile.

Class: Label
    Definition: A simple text tag that displays uneditable words on the screen.

    Usage: Used to add headings and titles within the form. For example,
             writing "Username" or "Email" right next to empty typing boxes, making it
             instantly clear what specific data needs to be typed and exactly where.

Class: Entry
    Definition: A blank, single-line text box where a human can
                 type information using a keyboard.

    Usage: Placed specifically to collect user data. Once text is typed via the
          keyboard, the backend script physically extracts that exact text from inside
          this box. A specific setting is also used here to hide password characters,
          turning them into solid dots for security.

Class: Button
    Definition: A clickable switch on the screen that triggers
                 a specific action or command when pressed.

    Usage: Placed at the very bottom of the form. When clicked with a mouse,
             it acts as the trigger that starts the background engine, extracting the filled
             data and sending it straight to the automated browser.

2. The Alert Module (tkinter.messagebox)
    Definition: A built-in tool designed specifically to show
                small alert pop-ups or notification boxes on top of the main window.

    Usage: Used to flash a small success popup on the screen only after
            the entire automation process completely finishes, providing visual confirmation
            that the data has been successfully submitted to the server.

3. The Custom Engine (main.WebAutomation)
    Definition: The custom-built robot engine that connects to the Google
                Chrome browser and performs automated clicks and typing on the actual internet.

    Usage: Kept completely separate from the frontend visual form. Once text is pulled
            out of the GUI, the engine of this robot class is started in system memory. Then, that
            extracted text is handed over to this robot so it can open the internet and execute
            commands on the actual target website (DemoQA).